I got into security kind of by accident. I was working as an accountant, slowly trying to pivot into data analytics. I walked into the office around 8am one morning and my boss's PA was sitting there looking pale. She asked me if I knew anything about computers. I said a little. She turned her screen toward me and showed me a Word document, except it wasn't a Word document anymore. It was just gibberish. Then she showed me the other screen. The one asking for Bitcoin.
That was my introduction to ransomware. I was the "knows a little bit about PCs" guy, so I wasn't really doing anything. I was standing there watching. But it stuck with me. The whole thing felt unreal. The office had basically been broken into and nobody had broken in. I wanted to understand how that even worked.
Years later that curiosity turned into a career change. Now I'm an ERP & CRM Systems Administrator at Yamato. I run Epicor Kinetic and Salesforce, manage the integrations between them, and back up our sysadmin/network admin. On the side I'm finishing a BS in Applied Cybersecurity (Blue Team) at SANS Technology Institute, with seven GIAC certs along the way: GMON, GSOC, GCIA, GCIH, GSEC, GPYC, GFACT, plus Network+ and Security+.
What I actually want to do is threat hunt. Spend my days digging through logs and traffic looking for things that shouldn't be there. The IT work has been good prep for that. Production environments are messy in ways the textbooks don't really prepare you for, and I think that perspective will be useful in a SOC.
